analysis_text:
> DETAILS
This is a Marschak-Machina triangle. It represents all lotteries over three ordered outcomes as points inside a triangle, where the top corner corresponds to certainty of the best outcome and the right corner corresponds to certainty of the worst outcome. The position of a point reflects the probabilities assigned to these outcomes, with the probability of the remaining middle outcome determined implicitly so that all probabilities sum to one. Moving within the triangle changes probability mass across outcomes while keeping payoffs fixed, so the geometry represents probability tradeoffs rather than changes in outcomes. Indifference curves drawn over the triangle summarize preferences, with straight parallel lines characterizing expected utility and systematic curvature or fanning indicating violations of it.

The preferences in this triangle are clearly non-linear: the implied indifference curves are not parallel and their orientation changes across the simplex. In the upper-left region, many comparisons run close to horizontal, indicating that lotteries are evaluated mainly by the probability of the best outcome, with relatively little sensitivity to whether the remaining probability falls on the middle versus the worst outcome. Lower in the triangle, the implied curves tilt upward and fan out, meaning that increases in the probability of the worst outcome must be compensated by increasingly large increases in the probability of the best outcome to keep a lottery equally attractive. Overall, the pattern suggests a strong focus on securing the best outcome, coupled with pronounced downside aversion when the chance of the best outcome is not already high.
tldr_text: This model mostly cares about how likely the best result is; if that chance isn't high, it becomes much more cautious about increasing the chance of the worst result.
